{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17565726","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17565726"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T23:31:09+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T23:31:09+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18295"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"18295","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/18295"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.02,0.51,0.18,0.15,0.13]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"11013"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"111621"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"11013","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/11013"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18295"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"93698"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"24"},{"type":"tags","id":"35"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"78"},{"type":"tags","id":"2067"},{"type":"tags","id":"4174"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"25564"},{"type":"contributions","id":"39810"},{"type":"contributions","id":"45445"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"111621","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/111621"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 56-year-old woman presents acutely on the surgical ward with sudden onset difficulty breathing two hours after cricopharyngeal pouch excision. The operation was uneventful. She has no significant medical history and takes no regular medications. On examination, she appears distressed with audible inspiratory stridor. Her pulse rate is 110/min, blood pressure 150/95 mmHg, respiratory rate 28/min, SpO2 94% on room air. There is obvious bruising and swelling around the surgical site in her neck (Image).\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate next step in management?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Await arrival of Code Blue team","Remove skin sutures","Immediate transfer to theatre","Non-rebreather mask and oxygen","Emergency cricothyroidotomy"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient presents with signs of post-operative neck haematoma causing airway compromise, a surgical emergency that requires immediate intervention. The presence of stridor, respiratory distress, and visible neck swelling indicates expanding haematoma compressing the airway. When approaching this critically unwell patient using the ABCDE approach, there is clearly airway compromise, so addressing this is the first priority.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ERemove skin sutures\u003C/strong\u003E is the most appropriate immediate action. Opening the wound at the bedside allows decompression of the haematoma and relieves pressure on the airway. This simple procedure can be life-saving and buys time for definitive management.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAwait arrival of Code Blue team\u003C/strong\u003E would cause dangerous delay in a situation requiring immediate action. The patient\u0027s condition could deteriorate rapidly while waiting for the team to arrive, potentially leading to complete airway obstruction.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EImmediate transfer to theatre\u003C/strong\u003E without first decompressing the haematoma could result in complete airway obstruction during transport. The priority is to relieve the immediate threat to the airway before considering definitive surgical management.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ENon-rebreather mask and oxygen\u003C/strong\u003E alone would not address the underlying cause of airway compromise. While oxygen therapy might temporarily improve oxygenation, it would not prevent progression of airway compression from the expanding haematoma.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EEmergency cricothyroidotomy\u003C/strong\u003E is too aggressive as a first step when a simpler intervention (removing sutures) would likely resolve the immediate crisis. Additionally, the presence of post-operative swelling and distorted anatomy would make this procedure particularly challenging and risky.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Post-operative neck haematoma causing airway compromise requires immediate wound decompression at bedside.","Removing skin sutures is the first step in managing post-operative neck haematoma to relieve airway compression.","Delay in treating post-operative neck haematoma can lead to rapid airway obstruction and death."],"references":["Galluzzi F, Garavello W. Complications of revision surgery in case of bleeding after thyroid surgery: A systematic review.Eur Ann Otorhinolaryngol Head Neck Dis. 2023; 140:171-76."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"93698"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18295"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"21362"}]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"media","id":"21362","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/21362"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/8v4yZjkRoHD20l6OrlIFLBRaXyhuYm.jpg","thumbUrl":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/8v4yZjkRoHD20l6OrlIFLBRaXyhuYm.jpg","isProcessed":true,"width":456,"height":324}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"93698","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/93698"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-08-17T14:18:28+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-08-17T14:20:09+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"11013"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"111621"}}},"meta":{"canDele